<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-034-203 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 457 421</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Oct 14 1991 v25 n41 p87(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Are corporate codes enough? Maybe not. (corporate codes of ethics)(Executive Report: IS Ethics)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rifkin, Glenn.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many information systems (IS) professionals contend that companycodes of ethics are sufficient to deal with ethical issuesspecific to IS operations, but this may not be true.andP;  Anexamination of a general code used by United Technologies Corpreveals the 21-page code does not address computer technology.andO;Relying on corporate ethics codes to address IS is problematicbecause not all firms even have corporate codes.andP;  A recent poll byRobert Half International Inc indicates that only about 44 percentof the largest firms in the US have a commitment to a written codeof ethics.andP;  Some experts do not believe IS ethics codes arenecessary because the prime focus of IS is to successfully use ISoperations to reach business goals, which does not necessitate acode of ethics.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Robert Half International Inc. (Surveys).andO;Topic:     EthicsGoals and ObjectivesSurveyInformation systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>